explanation:
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Determines whether the token acquisition and any side-effects (e.g. refcount increment, transaction start, error handling) occur. Needed to know when the if-body executes and what observable state changes it causes.
- OS_GenericSeek_Impl: Performs the seek operation. Essential to decide if this executed operation has observable effects (file position, I/O state) and therefore is not dead.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Releases the token (likely decrements refcount / ends transaction). Required to determine whether the release has observable effects on program behaviour (resource lifetime, side-effects) and thus whether that call is dead.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: Called (per call graph) by OS_ObjectIdGetById; needed to understand transactional/refcount semantics initiated when acquiring the object token.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish: Called by OS_ObjectIdRelease; needed to understand what release completes (commit/cleanup) and whether its removal would change behaviour.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Called by OS_ObjectIdGetById on error paths; needed to understand error-handling side-effects and whether earlier operations are necessary.
- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex: Part of GetById path; needed to see whether index conversion has side-effects that affect behaviour.
- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken: Part of GetById path; needed to understand how the token is formed and any side-effects relevant to correctness.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Called by OS_GenericSeek_Impl (per call graph); needed to see how the token maps to the underlying object and any side-effects of that mapping.
- OS_object_token_t, osal_id_t, int32, uint32: Type definitions used by OS_lseek. Required to interpret semantics (e.g. whether token holds ownership info) and to reason about observable effects of operations on those types.
- OS_SUCCESS: The success return value tested by the if; required to determine which branch is executed.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: Macro/constant parameters passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById that may change its behaviour (e.g. refcounting vs locking) and thus affect whether subsequent calls are necessary.

These symbols provide the implementations, side-effects, return semantics and type information needed to determine whether any executed operation in OS_lseek could be removed without changing program behaviour (i.e. whether it is dead code).
